For all positive integers $n$, let $f(n)=\log_{2002} n^2$. Find $f(11)+f(13)+f(14)$.

$f(n) = \log_{2002} n^2 = 2\log_{2002} n$
$f(11) = 2\log_{2002} 11$
$f(13) = 2\log_{2002} 13$
$f(14) = 2\log_{2002} 14$
$f(11)+f(13)+f(14) = 2\log_{2002} 11 + 2\log_{2002} 13 + 2\log_{2002} 14$
$= 2(\log_{2002} 11 + \log_{2002} 13 + \log_{2002} 14)$
$= 2\log_{2002} (11 \times 13 \times 14)$
$= 2\log_{2002} (11 \times 13 \times 2 \times 7)$
$= 2\log_{2002} (143 \times 14)$
$= 2\log_{2002} (2002)$
$= 2(1)$
$= 2$
Final Answer: $\boxed{2}$
